ont-size:12pt">.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.7pt; text-indent:-30.15pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Strategic Case has not considered alternative options for The United Kingdom to spend</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.55pt; text-indent:20.7pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">£50 Billion.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.55pt; text-indent:20.7pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 71.25pt; text-indent:-19.95pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The numbers quoted by HS2 are grossly incorrect.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.55pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">1.   Total Journey Times were not taken into account by KPMG.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1.1 Currently if you are travelling to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> from The West Midlands, your local train will stop at   </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Birmingham New St</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for your connection to London Euston.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In future, you and your luggage will have to leave </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">New St</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and travel by foot or public transport to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Curzon St</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to catch  HS2.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1.2 If you are travelling from the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Coventry</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> area, currently all </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Birmingham</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to London Euston trains stop at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Coventry</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, HS2 will not, and so there will be less trains per hour from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Coventry</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to Euston.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1.3 If you are currently travelling from The West Midlands to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Derby</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> or Nottingham, your local train will stop at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Birmingham New St</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for your connection to the centres of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Derby</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Nottingham</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In future, you and your luggage will have to go to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Curzon St</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, where the train will take you to</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Toton</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">/East Midlands Interchange, from where you will transfer to new rail links to existing conventional lines which go to the centres of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Derby</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Nottingham</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">These links have not been </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">costed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as part of the HS2 Project.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">HS2 quote the travel time to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Derby</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as 12 minutes and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Nottingham</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 15 minutes but omit the average waiting time between HS2 and the local train.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">2.   Conventional Train time improvements were not considered by KPMG.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.1 There are 3 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">pinchpoints</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> on the WCML which restrict the speed at which conventional trains can travel. These would take 5 or 6 years to re-engineer, not 17 years as stated by the Minister of Transport.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.2 Network rail are planning to introduce In-Cab signalling which will allow conventional trains to travel faster.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">3.   The KPMG was biased.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.1 It only considered a philosophy that was biased towards its paymaster, HS2 Ltd.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3.2 What is required is a totally independent report (Not from KPMG)..</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">4. There is no Capacity Problem on The West Coast </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Main Line</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.1 There are four simple tests to help us understand whether there is a capacity problem.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.2 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Seats Occupied. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The official figures show that WCML Intercity trains are only c59% full at</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">peak times (Ref. a).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Lower seat loadings than all other domestic long distance routes into any London Terminus.(Ref. b).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.3 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Train Configuration.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There are four first class carriages, which are a third full at peak (Ref. c). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.4 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Train Length. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">At present, trains are a mix of 9 and 11 carriages. 12 Carriage trains could be run to all destinations except </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Liverpool</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.5 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Train Paths</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Could more trains per hour be run at peak times?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Re-engineering 3 pinch points, and introducing In-Cab signalling will increase train speeds and therefore enable there to be more trains per hour.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.6 51M have shown that by reducing first class carriages to 3 per train and increasing train length to 12 per train, the number of seats per train will be 693, over four times the current average for the route of 164 per train. Network Rail has agreed these figures..</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It more than meets the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dft’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> forecast of passengers doubling by 2037.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In addition by dealing with the 3 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">pinchpoints</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> on the WCML and implementing In-Cab signalling, extra trains per hour can be run.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.7 So the above proves that there is no Intercity Capacity problem.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.8 Commuter capacity to Milton Keynes and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Northampton</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is currently a problem.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.9 There are simple solutions:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In the short term allow travellers to Milton Keynes to get off Virgin Trains at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Milton Keynes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Currently the trains stop there but only to pick up passengers.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In the medium term spend £260 million on a flyover at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Ledburn</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Junction and use faster commuter trains to increase the number of trains per hour. This could be completed in 5 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">years time</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4.10 Longer term, commuter services to Hemel Hempstead and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Watford</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to Euston need to be resolved, but a £50 Billion National Rail Service cannot be promoted as a sensible solution. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">5. The Strategic Case has not considered alternative options for The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> to spend £50Billion.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5.1 The Financial Times, The Economist, The Spectator and The Sunday Telegraph all reject the HS2 Project as a sensible way to spend £50 Billion.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5.2 Only 5% of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> travel is by train. There are so many other significant projects outstanding that would generate wealth in the North of England. Widening the M6, building new Motorways, getting rid of traffic jams that increase travel time to and from work on a daily basis.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5.3 Significantly more Capital Spending on Schools and Hospitals is required, but not available.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5.4 Upgrading all </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> conventional rail services is necessary.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">6. The numbers quoted by HS2 are grossly incorrect.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6.1 The Financial Times proved that the Peak Time Travel figures were incorrect by 50%.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6.2 Wider benefits of £15 billion are now claimed by HS2. 25 times the value implied in the January 2012 Analysis.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Passenger forecasts include an additional 45,000 return trips daily, generated by the introduction of HS2.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dividing £15 billion by 45,000 and by 300 effective days per annum provides £1,100 for each generated return trip. As only business travel will generate income, that equates to £3,700 per business trip.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Worse still, the benefit of a generated trip is usually only 50% of a pre-existing trip, and therefore each pre-existing  trip is generating £2200, and each pre-existing business trip is generating £7400 per annum. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Multiply 730 Million round trips per annum (Quoted by Network Rail) by £2,200 and it implies that </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">£1,600 Billion will be generated, which is greater than our Nation’s GDP. (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Ref.d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6.3 The most appropriate comparator for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dft</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> passenger forecasts is HS1 which has produced just 38% of its business case forecast; this throws considerable doubt on HS2 forecasts.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6.4 Communication Technology Improvements will reduce the need for business travel.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">British Telecom Plc. is already demonstrating a very sophisticated version of 3D Conferencing.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6.5 Jobs created by HS2 relate to the construction and maintenance of the HS2 Lines and Rolling Stock, and at Retail Outlets at the new stations. When asked, Birmingham Chamber of Commerce replied they had no idea what sort of additional jobs would be created by HS2.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6.6 HS2 will not create more freight capacity on the WCML, during the 10 years it will take to build Stage 2, HS2 will virtually demolish the current freight capacity between </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Lichfield</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and the North. (Ref. e)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6.7 HS2 cost/benefit ratio falls in the bottom 25% of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dft</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Intercity  Schemes and in the bottom 10% of their projects overall ( Ref. f ).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">References</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a) 2011 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Dft</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> figures released to High Court as part of The Judicial Review hearing on HS2 in December 2012.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">b) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">South East Route</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> utilisation Strategy (July 2011) page 55.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">c) see a).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d) Transport Watch, New Civil Engineer 7/11/13.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e) Lord Anthony Berkeley, Chairman, Rail freight Group.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">f) Henry </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Overman</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, Professor of Economic Geography, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">School</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of Economics.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><